{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17414545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17414545"},"attributes":{"position":38,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:52:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:52:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:47:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:47:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"16715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.05,0.85,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66523"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9406"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1318"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4176"},{"type":"tags","id":"4210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4213"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22263"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66523"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with a six-month history of post-coital bleeding and occasional spotting between periods. Her menstrual cycle is regular and unchanged. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She had normal cervical screening two years ago. She is in a monogamous relationship. She has had two vaginal deliveries, 10 and 12 years ago. She currently uses condoms for contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Speculum examination reveals a 2 cm red, smooth pedunculated lesion on a thin stalk protruding from the external cervical os. The surrounding cervix appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent hysteroscopy D\u0026C","Endometrial biopsy","Cervical co-test and polypectomy","High-vaginal swab only","Reassurance and review in three months"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with post-coital bleeding and intermenstrual spotting, with examination findings consistent with a cervical polyp. While cervical polyps are common benign growths that typically arise from the endocervical canal, any abnormal vaginal bleeding requires thorough investigation to exclude more serious pathology such as cervical cancer, particularly in the presence of post-coital bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical co-test and polypectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. The co-test (HPV and cytology testing) is essential as cervical cancer must be excluded in any woman with post-coital bleeding, even with a recent normal screening history and visible polyp. Simple polypectomy can usually be performed in the outpatient setting using local anaesthetic and will likely resolve the bleeding symptoms. Polypectomy can be achieved without surgery when the polyp is small and on a thin stalk - larger polyps with thick stalks or stalks extending into the cervical canal may require hysteroscopy. The polyp should be sent for histopathological examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent hysteroscopy D\u0026amp;C\u003C/strong\u003E is overly invasive for a cervical polyp with normal surrounding cervix. While hysteroscopy may be indicated if there are concerns about concurrent intrauterine pathology, it would not be first-line management. The location of the polyp in the external cervical os means it can be managed with simpler outpatient procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were concerns about endometrial pathology, particularly in women over 45 years with intermenstrual bleeding, or those with risk factors for endometrial hyperplasia. This patient\u0027s regular cycles, age under 45 years, and visible cervical polyp make endometrial sampling unnecessary as a first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-vaginal swab only\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate investigation for post-coital bleeding. While sexually transmitted infections can cause cervicitis and abnormal bleeding, the presence of a polyp requires specific management. Furthermore, post-coital bleeding always warrants cervical co-testing to exclude serious pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and review\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inappropriate. Post-coital bleeding is a red flag symptom that requires investigation, even with a visible benign cause such as a polyp. The polyp should be removed both for symptom management and to obtain tissue for histological examination. Additionally, cervical co-testing is essential to exclude underlying cervical pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-coital bleeding requires examination to exclude cervical cancer and other pathology.","Cervical polyps commonly present with post-coital or intermenstrual bleeding.","A cervical co-test (HPV and cytology) is essential in the investigation of abnormal vaginal bleeding."],"references":["TeachMeObGyn. Cervical Polyps [Internet]. TeachMeObGyn; [cited 2024 Nov 30]. Available from: https://teachmeobgyn.com/gynaecology/cervix/cervical-polyps/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51976"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T18:33:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T18:34:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9406"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66523"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt